First, let's define the matrix \emph{A} and \emph{b}:

\texttt{~~~A~=~{[}X1\^{}2~X1~1;~X2\^{}2~X2~1;~X3\^{}2~X3~1;~X4\^{}2~X4~1{]};}\\\texttt{~~~b~=~{[}Y1;~Y2;~Y3;~Y4{]};}

Next, we solve \emph{A\textsuperscript{T}A\textbf{a} =
A\textsuperscript{T}\textbf{b}} for \textbf{a}:

\texttt{~~~a~=~(A'*A)\textbackslash{}(A'*b);~~~\%~or~a~=~inv(A'*A)*A'*b;}

The vector \emph{a} now holds the coefficients of \emph{q(x)}, so we can
define the function \emph{q(x)}

\texttt{~~~q~=~@(x)~a{[}1{]}*x\^{}2~+~a{[}2{]}*x~+~a{[}3{]};}

and finally plot this anonymous function:

\texttt{~~~fplot(q,~{[}X1~X4{]})~~\%~or~plot(linspace(X1,~X4),~q(linspace(X1,~X4)))}

\emph{Note:} We assume that the \emph{x}-values are well-ordered,
\emph{x\textsubscript{1} ≤ x\textsubscript{2} ≤ x\textsubscript{3} ≤
x\textsubscript{4}}. If this is not the case, replace \emph{X1} with
\emph{min({[}X1, X2, X3, X4{]})} and \emph{X4} with \emph{max({[}X1, X2,
X3, X4{]})}.
